# Electron & IPC Patterns

## Project Structure

```
electron/
├── main/
│   ├── index.ts          # App lifecycle (BrowserWindow, app events)
│   ├── ipc/handlers.ts   # All ipcMain.handle() registrations
│   └── services/         # Business logic (runs in main process)
│       └── imageCompress.ts
└── preload/
    └── index.ts          # contextBridge API exposure
```

## Adding a New IPC Handler

**1. Define the API type** in `src/types/index.ts` under `ElectronAPI`:

```typescript
export interface ElectronAPI {
  // existing methods...
  newMethod: (arg: NewArg) => Promise<NewResult>
}
```

**2. Register the handler** in `electron/main/ipc/handlers.ts`:

```typescript
ipcMain.handle('new-method', async (_, arg: NewArg) => {
  // business logic
  return result
})
```

**3. Expose via context bridge** in `electron/preload/index.ts`:

```typescript
contextBridge.exposeInMainWorld('electronAPI', {
  // existing methods...
  newMethod: (arg) => ipcRenderer.invoke('new-method', arg)
})
```

## Important Rules

- **Image processing** (Sharp) belongs in `electron/main/services/`, never in renderer
- **Do not** use `require()` — ESM only (`"type": "module"`)
- **Main process** runs Node.js APIs; **preload** bridges to renderer
- **Renderer** accesses Electron via `window.electronAPI` (fully typed)
- All IPC uses `ipcMain.handle` / `ipcRenderer.invoke` (async request-response)
- Progress/events use `webContents.send()` + `ipcRenderer.on()` in renderer
